   <abstract>The ATRX (alpha-thalassemia X-linked mental retardation) gene codes for a multifunctional protein, that is an ATP-dependent chromatin remodeler that assists in the deposition of histone variant H3.3 in telomeric and pericentromeric heterochromatin. Mutations in the ATRX gene are found in patients with the rare genetic disorder ATRX syndrome, resulting in a severe developmental disease that primarily affects human males, characterized by severe intellectual disability, microcephaly, and seizures. ATRX is known to bind the repetitive regions to maintain genomic stability for regions such as ribosomal DNA, minisatellites, telomeres, and pericentric heterochromatin. However, little is known about the consequence of the complete loss of ATRX on chromatin dynamics and the chromatin remodeling function of ATRX in nucleosome organization. Here, we knocked out the ATRX gene utilizing CRISPR/Cas9 in Retinal Pigment Epithelial cells (RPE1), a female cell line, to determine the impact ATRX loss has on global gene expression and chromatin marks, using X-chromosome inactivation (XCI) as a model. We found that lack of ATRX causes dispersion of the repressive heterochromatin marks histone H3 trimethylated at lysine 27 (H3K27me3) and histone H2A ubiquitinated at lysine 119 (H2AK119Ub). The ATRX knockdown cells also exhibited decompaction of inactive X-chromosome (Xi) and caused the appearance of new intense intranuclear chromatin foci with H2AK119Ub staining. Additionally, we employed an MNase (Micrococcal Nuclease) based assay to monitor genome-wide changes to nucleosome occupancy and sensitivity near transcription start sites (TSS) in both RPE1 and male human colorectal carcinoma cell line, HCT116. Nucleosomal occupancy around TSS maintains a similar profile in the ATRX-deleted cells, although the average occupancy was significantly reduced. However, nucleosome sensitivity showed an unexpected pattern of major genome-wide dispersion. Our results indicate an additional role of ATRX in genome organization beyond the known function of maintaining genome stability.</abstract>
